an even understand being reluctant to place a 4 year old in full day kindy. &#10;What I don't at all understand is deciding to redshirt one's summer birthday child when the child is still a toddler, thus making it impossible to assess the child's actual readiness. What happens if the pre-K teacher thinks the child is *perfectly* ready for kindergarden? Would the parents still choose to hold the child back so he isn't the smallest/youngest/least mature? "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="760" language="en" documentId="5172" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="JenMomtoLexi+" date="04/04/2012" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://community.babycenter.com/post/a32503567/yet_another_redshirting_debate?cpg=14" topic="redshirting" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="5172" notes="" title="Yet another redshirting debate"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="383"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="384" end="760"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>